			<ns0:name>brettw@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/brettw@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Our returned value matches most other systems like Windows and posix. It also diverges from what PPAPI does in other cases. Network stuff, for example, always provide the number of bytes "consumed" and this makes the most sense for these operations.

Even if it might be more convenient, it would be confusing if it diverged from what people are used to writing, and so I don't think would be a good idea.

I'd probably just write a wrapper function if you prefer to do things differently.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-04-22T19:43:13.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-04-22T19:43:13.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 2 by brettw@chromium.org</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1718#c2" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/1718/comments/full/2" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>